                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3962: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-08T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 8, 1922—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 8—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>364. Your 209, September 1, 5 p.m. Legation has repeatedly brought this situation
                    to the attention of the Foreign Office, Ministry of Finance and Ministry of
                    Communication[s]. Payments continue to be made fairly regularly on 14,000,000
                    treasury notes,<note n="74" xml:id="d593fn74">See telegram no. 19, Jan. 21, from
                        the Minister in China, <ref target="#pg_762">p. 762</ref>.</note>
                    consolidated internal loans, and now on 96,000,000 while Government is
                    indifferent to defaulted foreign obligations. Full report follows.<note n="73"
                        xml:id="d593fn73">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
